According to the project website (https://mesospim.org/), at least 12 builds are in operation and follow-up work provides detailed protocols for tissue clearing21.

An implementation of open microscopy in its purest form in which ideas and experimental designs are shared online and on social media sometimes even before experimental realizations take place has been pioneered by Andrew York (https://andrewgyork.github.io/).
The open source hardware association (OSHWA) offers a guideline to maintain a good quality of openness in projects (https://www.oshwa.org/sharing-best-practices/).
As a case in point, the ¬µManager community managed to collect hundreds of device adapters (https://micro-manager.org/Device_Support).

As a recent example, the need for an adaptable image viewer interacting with the Python environment kickstarted the impressive and community-driven development of napari (https://zenodo.org/record/3555620).

One recent example of open microscopy hitting the shelves is the openFrame microscope developed by the French group and commercially available via Cairn research (https://www.cairn-research.co.uk/product/openframe-microscope/).
Additional resources A list of hardware and software projects, repositories and additional resources can be found on https://github.com/HohlbeinLab/OpenMicroscopy.

ezcox is an open source R package under GPL-3 license and it is free available at https://github.com/ShixiangWang/ezcox and https://cran.r-project.org/package=ezcox.
Instructions on how to install, use ezcox are presented in the public GitHub repository (https://github.com/ShixiangWang/ezcox).

To illustrate how to use core features of ezcox for omics data, we provided a more practical vignette at https://shixiangwang.github.io/ezcox-adv-usage/ to show how to analyze mRNA expression of a gene list containing oncogenes and tumor suppressors in TCGA.

Since its release, ezcox has been downloaded for more than 14,000 times (according to the API for CRAN package download counts, from the RStudio CRAN mirror, https://cranlogs.r-pkg.org/) and utilized in multiple published cancer studies[10]‚Äì[13] around the world.
